Mon Jan 23 00:37:17 GMT 2023

What has been changed in that snapshot that breaks datapacks? ü´£

Apollo
Mon Jan 23 00:38:29 GMT 2023

currently biomes have a `precipitation` field that decides whether rain, snow, or neither happens

Apollo
Mon Jan 23 00:39:08 GMT 2023

in 1.19.3 it becomes a `has_precipitation` field with either `true` or `false`

Apollo
Mon Jan 23 00:39:46 GMT 2023

luckily this change isn't that huge; you can just include both fields and the pack will work on 1.19.3 and 1.19.4

There's mountain ranges far larger than those you would find in vanilla, underground rivers that can go on for thousands of blocks, and more interesting terrain generation for you to go out and find on your adventures with this pack. > > This pack also improves on vegetation as well, with vastly improved oak and birch trees (with more overhauled trees coming soon!), improved river generation, and other smaller terrain changes. On top of this, there are over 25 new biomes and biome variants for you to explore. All of this is done without adding a single new block or item.

Sat Apr 22 21:44:11 +0000 2023

Fabric ```java public class TectonicFabric implements ModInitializer { public static final ResourceLocation TECTONIC = new ResourceLocation(TectonicConstants.MOD_ID, "tectonic"); public static final ResourceLocation TERRATONIC = new ResourceLocation(TectonicConstants.MOD_ID, "terratonic"); @Override public void onInitialize() { if (FabricLoader.getInstance().isModLoaded("terralith")) { FabricLoader.getInstance().getModContainer(TectonicConstants.MOD_ID).ifPresent((modContainer -> ResourceManagerHelper.registerBuiltinResourcePack(TERRATONIC, modContainer, "Terratonic", ResourcePackActivationType.DEFAULT_ENABLED))); } else { FabricLoader.getInstance().getModContainer(TectonicConstants.MOD_ID).ifPresent((modContainer -> ResourceManagerHelper.registerBuiltinResourcePack(TECTONIC, modContainer, "Tectonic", ResourcePackActivationType.DEFAULT_ENABLED))); } } } ```

Apollo
Sat Apr 22 21:44:15 +0000 2023

Forge ```java public class TectonicForge { public TectonicForge() { IEventBus modEventBus = FMLJavaModLoadingContext.get().getModEventBus(); modEventBus.addListener(this::setupBuiltInStandardDatapack); } private void setupBuiltInStandardDatapack(final AddPackFindersEvent event) { if (event.getPackType() == PackType.SERVER_DATA && ModList.get().isLoaded("terralith")) { var resourcePath = ModList.get().getModFileById(TectonicConstants.MOD_ID).getFile().findResource("resourcepacks/terratonic"); var pack = Pack.readMetaAndCreate("builtin/base_terratonic", Component.literal("Terratonic"), false, (path) -> new PathPackResources(path, resourcePath, false), PackType.SERVER_DATA, Pack.Position.BOTTOM, PackSource.BUILT_IN); event.addRepositorySource((packConsumer) -> packConsumer.accept(pack)); } else { var resourcePath = ModList.get().getModFileById(TectonicConstants.MOD_ID).getFile().findResource("resourcepacks/tectonic"); var pack = Pack.readMetaAndCreate("builtin/base_tectonic", Component.literal("Tectonic"), false, (path) -> new PathPackResources(path, resourcePath, false), PackType.SERVER_DATA, Pack.Position.BOTTOM, PackSource.BUILT_IN); event.addRepositorySource((packConsumer) -> packConsumer.accept(pack)); } } ```

a cats
Sat Apr 29 16:27:01 +0000 2023

if the mod's open source you should just be able to download the code, open it in an IDE like intellij, find the class that has the relevant code, change the value then put ./gradlew build in the IDE's terminal to generate the new mod file Bear in mind a lot of the time mods don't use the entity's ID in the code for things like spawning or checking for the type, they reference the entity type or the entity's class, so it may not be as simple as you expect to make it work with another mod Also unless the mod specifically allows it, you should not distribute your modified version of the mod

Blissyin
Fri Jun 23 01:43:05 +0000 2023

Hey im using the "Deeper Oceans" datapack and ive been wondering if i can make them even deeper by editing the datapack? Im using "shattered world limits" mod, so i can make the oceans quite a bit deeper.

Blissyin
Fri Jun 23 01:43:26 +0000 2023

And if i can, which values should i edit to achieve said thing

Apollo
Fri Jun 23 02:02:07 +0000 2023

you technically can but you have to go into the datapack files to do do

Apollo
Fri Jun 23 02:03:52 +0000 2023

in the `warped_gradient.json` file, you should see this at around line 30: ```json { "type": "minecraft:range_choice", "input": "minecraft:y", "min_inclusive": -64, "max_exclusive": 16, "when_in_range": { "type": "minecraft:y_clamped_gradient", "from_y": -64, "to_y": 16, "from_value": 0.875, "to_value": 0.625 }, "when_out_of_range": 0 } ``` Change both instances of -64 to your new world bottom. That will likely make oceans FAR too deep, you'll need to increase the `from_value` to compensate (I'd recommend testing in increments of 0.25)

Blissyin
Fri Jun 23 02:06:37 +0000 2023

Yeah ive been tinkering around a bit. Its created trenches that go very deep! But they seem a bit disconnected from everything else. Gonna experiment. Thanks for the info!

Blissyin
Fri Jun 23 02:34:25 +0000 2023

but if you're already removing biomes, you could *easily* edit the advancement to remove the biomes from there as well

Ian
Wed Jul 19 18:59:29 +0000 2023

catter
Wed Jul 19 18:59:36 +0000 2023

its even easier than removing biomes

catter
Wed Jul 19 18:59:36 +0000 2023

and yes, it only applies to vanilla (unless a mod/datapack overrides it to add their own)

catter
Wed Jul 19 19:00:15 +0000 2023

for example, if you were removing Swamp, you would simply delete these 3 lines from the advancement: https://github.com/misode/mcmeta/blob/data/data/minecraft/advancements/adventure/adventuring_time.json#L1005-L1007

Ian

catter
Wed Jul 19 19:06:00 +0000 2023

there's a *ton* of options. - <#994832645886320670>, but this is a small server compared to the other options - Stardust Labs (https://discord.gg/stardustlabs) has a *ton* of people, with designated channels for this kind of stuff (and overlaps with knowledgable members of this server) - MC Configs (https://discord.gg/EjrKNBU) is smaller, but has a ton of *super* knowledgable people. although is more geared for worldgen - MC Commands (https://discord.gg/QAFXFtZ) is another large server, but exists for the sole purpose of helping with commands, function datapacks, and i suppose a bit of worldgen - MC Worldgen (https://discord.gg/BuBGds9) is similar to above, but specifically *modded* worldgen

Deepwoker
Fri Nov 17 18:54:47 GMT 2023

How do i install the datapack

Deepwoker
Fri Nov 17 18:54:51 GMT 2023

the tectonic one

Varley
Fri Nov 17 19:59:02 GMT 2023

Download it, leave it zipped. Make a new world, select this datapacks button and drag and drop the zip file into the folder that button opens up, then you'll see a window similar to resource packs where you can apply it. That should be it. If you're using the new, ugly 1.20 UI then the Data Packs button should be selectable through the tabs at the top, just look around and you'll see it. If you want to add it to a pre-existing world, I don't think you can, but then again it's been a while since I've been in the datapack scene so maybe it's doable now. If that is the case, open your minecraft saves folder and look for a folder named "datapacks" and put it in there, but again, I'm pretty sure adding world-gen packs to pre-existing saves is not good for them.

Boba194230

https://modrinth.com/mod/patched

Apollo
Fri Nov 17 23:46:43 GMT 2023

the issue with Patched is that the inter-pack compatibility Lithostitched has is just entirely nonexistent

Apollo
Fri Nov 17 23:48:24 GMT 2023

for example: - One mod adds custom fossils to Desert biomes - Another mod adds a custom desert biome With Lithostitched, the first mod just targets the `#c:desert` biome tag and all mods that add their desert biomes to the tag will automatically get the custom fossils With Patched, each mod needs their desert biome files patched manually

Apollo
Fri Nov 17 23:50:14 GMT 2023

Lithostitched will also in the future supply way more than just worldgen modifiers

Sun Nov 19 21:19:03 GMT 2023

Hey I'm learning how datagen works and I have a question. I've been using Apollo's method to remove the lava below -64 using a geode feature. Now I want to make it so the deeper you go the more diamonds you can find up to -128 to do so I would need to modify height range for placed features of diamonds but the default values are like -80 / 80 does this mean in vanilla is only the upper part of the trapezoid shape?

Apollo
Sun Nov 19 21:19:49 GMT 2023

yes, in vanilla its just the top half of the trapezoid

Wofrion
Sun Nov 19 21:20:23 GMT 2023

So I just need to transpose the shape a certain amount to get the same distribution but deeper yes?

Apollo
Sun Nov 19 21:21:07 GMT 2023

if you push the bottom of the world to -128, the diamond layer will snap the center of the triangle to y-128

Wofrion
Sun Nov 19 21:21:39 GMT 2023

Oh really?

Wofrion
Sun Nov 19 21:21:57 GMT 2023

Why

Apollo
Sun Nov 19 21:23:05 GMT 2023

`ore_diamond` doesn't use absolute coordinates, it uses values relative to the bottom of the world

Apollo
Sun Nov 19 21:23:08 GMT 2023

```json { "type": "minecraft:height_range", "height": { "type": "minecraft:trapezoid", "min_inclusive": { "above_bottom": -80 }, "max_inclusive": { "above_bottom": 80 } } }, ```

Apollo
Sun Nov 19 21:23:49 GMT 2023

so instead of below from y-80 to y80, it's 80 blocks below the bottom (normally -144) to 80 blocks above the bottom (normally 16)

Nostalgion
Sun Nov 19 21:26:01 GMT 2023

It isn't really fair to pair those structures against each other - Desert and jungle temples are single tiny repetitive structures with nothing but 1 simple trap and a bit of loot - Mineshafts are expansive underground structures with some mining possibilities and loot - Villages are home to villagers and serve as a place of rest and converse in an otherwise deadly world - Mansions, ancient cities, bastions, and monuments (maybe pillager outposts) serve as extensions to the game world, they, and the following group, are randomly generated structures that pose a challenge with a good bit of reward for conquering it - Strongholds, end cities, and fortresses are for gameplay progression for blaze rods, the end, and elytras, so people are more likely to see and explore them during a world
